The simple moments are often the best ones. An intimate elopement at home for a couple of hours is sometimes all that you need. Not overthink things or make anything complicated. Thanks Rachel & Andreas for sharing that precious time with me. 
I’m catching up a bit in posting all that happened this year. And there is a lot to share.

Hey it’s been a while, right?! 2022 has been my biggest season since I started in 2012. I shot more than 45 weddings last year (last one was on new year’s eve). So taking a long pause was more than necessary. To get some rest of course, but also to put the camera down a bit. 
Taking the time to simply enjoy my family, my friends and do something else than taking pictures almost everyday. 
It has always been something very important for me to do to be able to recharge my creativity. Especially when work life has been so intense. 
So I’m finally catching with posting some of my favorite from last year. Here is Francesca & Daniel in Southampton on Long Island. Genuine and amazing couple that me and @yanicklesperance have been so lucky to work with.

Ariel & Andrew’s at the Windrift Hall. This wedding happened during the eight rainy saturdays in row we had last September and October. 
It was the first wedding season where I had so much rain. But we played with it, avoided it and sometime shot in between two episodes. But we always find a way to get the best of the day.

I heard you!
After receiving frequent requests for standalone couples sessions I decided to create a one-time offer!

Mini sessions make a great gift and allow you to hold onto memories and milestones of a relationship.
Yesterday marked my 10-year anniversary to Caroline and we feel so grateful to have had so many sessions over the years. 

Check out the link in bio NOW.
Booking are open for a limited time.
